                    <span>A lot of thought and effort went into this report and the results are impressive and without bias.
<br />
<br />The 13 chapters of this document can be broken down into three categories:
<br />
<br />The first describes the events that unfolded on September 11th, 2001 from the air (Chapter 1) and the ground (Chapter 9). These two chapters are real page-turners and describe the tragic events comprehensively and in vivid detail. These two chapters should be read by all Americans and anyone effected by the tragedy.
<br />
<br />The second category deal with the U.S. Government agencies responsible for fighting terrorism and the intelligence that they have gathered on Al-Qaeda (unfortunately most of the information was obtained after the attack). These chapters were a little tough to get through and understand completely. This is not, however, the fault of the Commission, but a symptom of how Byzantine and bureaucratic our government really is. There was, however, a lot of interesting and thought-provoking information contained in these chapters. For example, Al Qaeda and Osama Bin Laden were top priorities of the Clinton Administration, but Clinton consciously did not publicize their efforts in order to prevent Al Qaeda from gaining in popularity. This secrecy, coupled with bureaucracy, lack of inertia, and fear of retribution prevented any action or results coming from their talks and planning. These chapters also debunk several commonly held conspiracy theories including hijackers meeting with the Iraqi government and Saudi nationals being granted exemptions from flight restrictions.
<br />
<br />The final category contains the conclusions and recommendations. It is quite clear that a complete overhaul of the intelligence and counter-terrorism units of the government is required. The recommendations presented here are comprehensive and well thought out, but also require significant funding and resources. Hopefully, they will not fall upon deaf ears.</span>
                  
